        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 33-year-old Czech woman with a slender build, dark circles under her eyes, and a noticeably tense posture. She works as a graphic designer at a Prague advertising agency, spending eight or more hours a day in front of high-resolution monitors. She describes her recurring headaches as intense, throbbing pain predominantly on one side of her head, often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and a strong sensitivity to light and sound [SNOMED:G43.9]. During attacks she retreats to a dark, quiet room and finds it nearly impossible to continue working.\n\n{patientName} lives with her partner in a flat in Vinohrady district. She is sociable and enjoys weekend cycling along the Vltava river, visiting art galleries, and cooking with friends. However, her migraine attacks — occurring approximately 6–8 times per month and lasting anywhere from several hours to over a day [MEDDIALOG:G43.9:2] — have significantly curtailed her social life and professional performance. She has recently started tracking her headache diary, noting triggers that include poor sleep, menstruation, and stress.\n\nShe reports that at the onset of an attack she often experiences burping and nausea before the headache peaks [SNOMED:G43.9]. Photophobia is consistently prominent, forcing her to close all blinds and wear sunglasses even indoors [SNOMED:G43.9]. She occasionally vomits during severe episodes [SNOMED:G43.9], which further exhausts her and delays return to normal activities.\n\n{patientName} maintains a relatively healthy lifestyle — she does not smoke and drinks alcohol only socially. She consumes two to three cups of coffee per day and has noticed that skipping her morning coffee can occasionally precipitate a headache. Her diet is balanced but she has read about gut-brain axis connections and has begun experimenting with dietary modifications following a case report linking low-FODMAP diet to migraine improvement [PMID:38108544]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:75d4e078-3456-440b-a054-1d96fe52393a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was first diagnosed with migraine at age 21, when she presented to her general practitioner with recurrent severe unilateral headaches accompanied by nausea and photophobia [SNOMED:G43.9]. She has no prior hospitalisations specifically for migraine but has attended emergency outpatient neurology consultations on two occasions during exceptionally prolonged attacks lasting more than 36 hours [MEDDIALOG:G43.9:2].\n\nShe has no other significant chronic illnesses. There is no history of hypertension, epilepsy, or psychiatric disorder. Her menstrual cycles are regular, and she notes a clear perimenstrual worsening of her migraine frequency. She tried oral contraceptives at age 25 but discontinued them after observing increased headache frequency, a clinically plausible effect.\n\n{patientName} has no history of cardiovascular disease and takes no anticoagulants. She is aware that certain medications can worsen migraine, as described in literature on direct oral anticoagulants [PMID:37582651]. She previously used naproxen 500 mg for acute attacks [MEDDIALOG:G43.9:2] with moderate benefit, and was subsequently prescribed sumatriptan after a neurology referral. She reports no improvement with over-the-counter analgesics alone for severe attacks. She has been started on propranolol as prophylaxis. She has no known drug allergies except a penicillin allergy. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol rarely. She is currently not pregnant."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}